Today’s lesson is going to focus on greeting other when coming or leaving, and introductions using names and correct pronouns

PRONOUNS

First going to go through pronouns using the chart below

We have singular pronouns and plural pronouns, which I will be going through 

 I, you, he, she, we, it, they – first say what the pronouns are and then use them in a sentence

I am going to the market

Singular pronoun

You are going to school

Singular pronoun

I now pronounce you husband and wife

Can be used in a plural setting

Plural pronoun

He is going to the store

Singular pronoun

Masculine 

She is going to the mall

Singular pronoun

Feminine

We (you and i) are learning English

Plural pronoun

It is a green ball

Singular pronoun

They are going to the restaurant 

Plural pronoun

DO EXERCISE OF FILLING IN THE CORRECT PRONOUN BELOW (stopped before 11)

























































































































GREETINGS AND LEAVE-TAKINGS

Important vocabulary for greetings and leave-takings

Today

Today is October 20th

Tomorrow

Tomorrow will be October 21st 

Yesterday

Yesterday was October 19th  

Good

I am good

Well

I am well

Fine

I am fine

What

What’s up?

How

How are you doing?

Greetings – they are used when you meet someone

Hi

Hello

Hey

Good morning – if you are meeting someone in the morning time 

Good afternoon – if you are meeting someone in the afternoon time 

Good evening – if you are meeting someone in the nighttime

Leave-takings – they are used when you are saying goodbye to someone

Goodbye

Bye

See you later

See you tomorrow

Other common questions/phrases when talking to someone:

If someone asks, “What is your name?”, you respond with:

My name is Nikita, nice to meet you

If someone asks, “How are you?” you can say:

I am good

I am fine

You answer with this when you are not doing very well

When you respond with this, the other person may ask “What’s wrong?”

If someone asks, “How are you doing?”, you can respond with:

I am doing well

I am doing okay

Not bad

Used if you are feeling just okay

“What’s up?” Is a more casual way of asking “how are you?”, you can respond with:

Nothing much!

Not much!

PRACTICE

If I ask you “what is your name?” what should your response be?

EXERCISE

https://www.english-at-home.com/lessons/speaking-exercise-greetings-introductions/
